<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs from
Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Britain signed on Friday an agreement on
cooperation on information exchanges between Cairo and Alexandria
stock exchanges and London Stock Exchange, local daily El-Ahram
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, the first of its kind between London and the
Arab stock markets, aims to develop the Egyptian capital market in
the framework of Egyptian plan to put its stock markets on
equal footing with the international ones.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has signed a contract to purchase an automated trading
system worth 1.7 million U.S. dollars for the Cairo and Alexandria
stock exchanges, the daily added.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- About 600 plants in Tunisia have been listed on the
"all-out renovation plan" as part of the Tunisian-EU agreement on
establishing a free-trade zone.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed in 1995 and covered a total of 2,000
factories, was aimed at creating the free trade zone within 12
years to enable the Tunisian economy to compete with the European
products gradually.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- In its monthly economic report, the Central Bank of
Egypt (CBE) said Saturday that the rate of inflation in Egypt fell
to 3.4 percent in March against 5.5 percent in the same month
last year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign reserves at the CBE hit 20.115 billion U.S. dollars
in March, an increase of 633 million dollars from the same month
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Chief of the Egyptian General Investment Authority
Ibrahim Fawzi said the exports of Egyptian free trade zones to
foreign markets went up by 33 percent in May over the same month
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The volume of these exports rose from 30.4 million U.S. dollars
in May 1997 to 40.6 million last month.
</P>
<P>
Fawzi attributed the increase to many facilities offered by
the Egyptian government to investors in the free trade zones and
the decision of the EU member states to open their markets for the
exports of Egyptian free trade zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
