<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Returns to World Cup with Opener Against Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia, barred from qualifying for
the last World Cup in the United States, returned to the finals to
face Iran in their Group F opener in Saint-Etienne on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The internal strifes in the nation have cost the footballers dear
with their exclusion from the 1992 and 1996 European Championship.
</P>
<P>
However, their stunning 12-1 aggregate victory over former
powerhouse Hungary sent a strong signal that they are still a power to
reckon with at international level.
</P>
<P>
Spearheading the Yugoslav attack in France will be the outstanding
striker Predrag Mijatovic, the star who scored 14 goals in
qualification round and netted the winner for Real Madrid in the
European Cup final.
</P>
<P>
The simple fact that the 29-year-old finished runner-up after
Ronaldo for the 1997 European Footballer of Year indicates he should
be among the top cream in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav midfield is solid with such talents like Dragan
Stojkovic, Sinisa Mihajlovic and Vladimir Jugovic.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary to a Yugoslavian camp full of European
professionals, the Iranians have only three German Bundesliga players
Karim Bagheri, Khodadad Azizi and Ali Daei.
</P>
<P>
As to fitness problem, goalkeeper Ahmad Abedzadeh is doubtful while
winger Satar Hamedani could also has a knee ligament problem.
</P>
<P>
On the Yugoslavian side Dejan Savicevic faces a late fitness test
on a knee problem and could be replaced by Dejan Stankovic.
</P>
<P>
Iranian coach Jalal Talebi would apparently rely on a better
teamwork in Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I know our opponents are good, with great football
experience. But on a bad day they could very well lose to a lesser
team.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally we play an offensive and open game. What's more, one of
our greatest assets is our teammanship," added Talebi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
