<HEADLINE> Roundup: Increasing Pressure on West as Japan Slides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 13 (Xinhua) - Japan's confirmation of its
recession has caused fears here that it could drag the West into
economic decline.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the recession announcement Friday, the Dow Jones
industrial average on Wall Street plunged another 100 points
during afternoon trading. Here in London, the FTSE 100 index fell
82.7 points to close at 5,769.8.
</P>
<P>
Official figures published show that Japan's gross domestic
product shrank by 1.3 percent in the three months to the end of
March, equivalent to a decline at an annual rate of 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
This follows a decline in the final quarter of last year, and
leaves Japan's GDP 0.7 percent lower than a year ago. This is the
first full-year decline since 1974.
</P>
<P>
"If there is negative growth this fiscal year, the Japanese
economy will have contracted two consecutive years, making this
the country's worst post-war recession," warned Robert Feldman,
economist at Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
The decline was sharper than expected by the markets, which had
forecast a fall of only about half a percent, and reflects both a
lack of confidence among consumers in Japan and a fall in exports
to the rest of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Ian Morris, senior international economist at HSBC Securities,
said, "Things are deteriorating quicker than anticipated. All
these government stimulus packages they keep having are unlikely
to boost the economy and capital spending is collapsing."
</P>
<P>
"There is no sign of a turn-around and if anything the economic
data we have for the second quarter is even worse. It is only a
matter of time before a big-name Japanese company goes under," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The decline in the Japanese economy has lead to fears that the
depreciation of the yen, which has fallen by 11 percent in the
past two months, will reach a stage where it destabilizes the
whole of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Alex Brummer, an economic analyst in the City, said, "In the
new global economy of open markets and large financial flows there
is no protection from a crisis of confidence."
</P>
<P>
"Japan's problem is that of the United States, Britain and
continental Europe," he added.
</P>
<P>
The swiftest response came in the world currency markets, where
the yen slid to its lowest level since late 1990 against the
dollar at 144.62, threatening to trigger another round of
competitive devaluations in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Although the cheaper yen will help Japan's exports, it will fan
protectionist sentiment in the U.S. and put renewed pressure on
other Asian countries which suffered big currency devaluations in
the first wave of the crisis late last year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that most worrying of all for the markets, a
new wave of instability could suck China into the currency
turmoil. However, so far China has resisted the temptation to
devalue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
