<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat to Reshuffle PNA Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat has asked the Palestinian
Legislative Council (PLC) to have another 10-day delay in its
no-confidence vote pending a cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
PLC Speaker Abu Ala confirmed in Ramallah, West Bank Saturday
that Arafat has sent a letter to him in which Arafat said that he
will, after consulting with other Palestinian leaders, announce a
PNA cabinet reshuffle, Jerusalem Media and Communication Center
(JMCC) reported.
</P>
<P>
"Chairman Arafat asked the council for a delay of ten days in
its no-confidence vote to announce a new cabinet, and Arafat is
totally convinced the cabinet change is part of necessary
comprehensive administrative improvement," Abu Ala said.
</P>
<P>
Several PLC members on May 28 first asked to have a
no-confidence vote against the PNA, accusing it of inaction and
the delay in formulating the 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
On May 31, the PLC asked the PNA Cabinet to further reallocate
the budget as asked by some PLC members and resubmit it to the PLC
in two weeks for approval, otherwise it will face a no-confidence
vote in the PLC.
</P>
<P>
Some PLC members in the past had threatened to submit a
no-confidence motion against the PNA to the PLC for voting,
saying the PNA had not implemented the long-promised reforms
following charges of high-level corruption and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had promised in the past to reshuffle the cabinet and
remove those corrupted ministers from the cabinet, but no
reshuffle has been made so far due to political reasons.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who is on an official visit to Italy, signed with the
Italian government on Friday an agreement under which Italy will
provide 20 million U.S. dollars of aid to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The PLC, formed in January 1996, has a total of 88
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
