<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Appeals for New Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Minister of Industries
Gholamreza Shafei on Saturday called for new foreign investment
in order to reinvigorate the country's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the Iran-Austria Joint
Economic Commission, Shafei said Iran welcomes new foreign
investment in its industries in order to realize its main goal
of gaining a bigger share in the world trade.
</P>
<P>
A recent report showed that Iran's share of world trade has
shrunk from 2.3 percent in 1975 to 0.34 percent in 1995, while its
non-oil exports only make up 0.06 percent of the world trade. It
was announced last month that Iran's total exports stood at 18.824
billion U.S. dollars, of which only 3 billion dollars were from
non-oil exports.
</P>
<P>
In order to reduce the country's strong dependence on oil
incomes, the government of President Mohammad Khatami has pledged
to introduce reforms in order to transform the oil-dependent
economy to a healthy one.
</P>
<P>
Shafei said that Tehran's appeal for foreign investment was
also aimed at creating more job opportunities for the young
generation. Official figures show that 800,000 young people will
join the country's labor force every year since 20 million of the
country's 60 million population are between 11 and 24 years old.
</P>
<P>
"Iran is interested in new investments to produce (spare)
parts, and presently has cooperation with France and South Korea
in this field," Shafei said.
</P>
<P>
On the Iranian-Austrian trade, he noted that the two countries
can cooperate in using the existing facilities to increase
trade. For example, Austria can take advantage of Iranian
transportation facilities to access the Central Asian markets, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for Iranian-Austrian cooperation in developing
Caspian Sea oil fields.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the meeting, Austrian Economic Minister Johann
Farnleitner expressed hope that Austria would succeed in
introducing Iran's many capabilities in economic and trade sectors
to the European Union (EU) and thus to lay the groundwork for more
Iran-EU cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Austria will try to enhance the Iran-EU dialog through
bringing about a change in Europe's political outlook of Iran,''
he said, adding that Austria is prepared to train the young
Iranian population how to achieve industrial and economic progress.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian official also called for Vienna-Tehran cooperation
in transportation, sugar, paper and auto parts industries as
well as in environment and forestry sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
