<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fernandez Double Lifts Mexico to 3-1 Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LYON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A second-half double from striker Luis
Hernandez lifted Mexico 3-1 over a 10-man South Korea in a Group E
match of the World Cup finals here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ha Seok Ju converted a free kick in the 28th minute to put South
Koreans ahead 1-0 but he was expelled from the pitch two minutes later
for tackling Jesus Ramirez from behind.
</P>
<P>
The Mexicans mounted all-out attacks since then but failed to
produce any result before a well-organized Korean defence.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts finally paid off six minutes into the second half,
when midfielder Jesus Ramirez kicked off a corner kick toward the goal
mouth.
</P>
<P>
Substitute Ricardo Pelaez jumped up but his head missed the ball,
which was deflected by South Korean midfielder Kim Do Keun before
landing in Pelaez's path.
</P>
<P>
Pelaez surged ahead to slot the ball home past goalkeeper Kim Byung
Ji.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez, the blond-haired forward who plays for Mexican club
Necaxa, then showed his killer instinct on the pitch in the 75th
minute, lobbing the ball into net pass Korean keeper Kim Byung Ji on a
long pass.
</P>
<P>
He was on target nine minutes later, blasting a 18-meter shot home
after receiving a pass from his Necaxa teammate Cuauhtemoc Blanco.
</P>
<P>
Blanco, who also made several scoring attempts, amused the Mexican
fans with his acrobatic frog-jumping pass when he was sandwiched by
two South Korean defenders.
</P>
<P>
Austrian referee flashed three yellow cards in seven minutes in the
first half of this fast-paced and volatile game.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Lee Min Sung and Mexicans Jaime Ordiales and Alberto
Aspe Garcia were the ones cautioned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
