<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Provides More Chances for Returned Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- When Dr. Shan Xueyi returned to
this east China metropolis after he finished his studies in
automatic control at a university in Britain, he did not expect to
be put in charge of technological research at the hot-rolled plant
of the Baoshan Iron and Steel Complex.
</P>
<P>
He found a solution to a temperature problem in the laminar
flow of the hot-rolled process, which saved the company some one
million-yuan losses a year.
</P>
<P>
Shan said, "An energetic city with a high-growth rate in China,
Shanghai provides many opportunities for returned students from
abroad to show their talent."
</P>
<P>
Shan is just one of the 16,000 returned students from overseas
who have started their careers in Shanghai. In the past two
decades, the city has sent 80,000 students to study abroad.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the Shanghai Municipal Government has enacted a
number of policies for opening various sectors for returned
students to find opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Duan Qihua, a lawyer who studied in the United States for five
years, returned to Shanghai to set up the Duan &AMP; Duan Law Office
in the city.
</P>
<P>
He said that, as the first of its kind in the country, the
office has successfully handled a number of transnational law
suits, and now it has a branch office in Seattle in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Chen Liangyu, deputy mayor of Shanghai, said that the city
needs a large number of talented people who know international
economic practices in the process of turning the city into an
international economic, financial and trade center by the year
2010.
</P>
<P>
"The returned students from abroad constitute a major force in
Shanghai's development," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 returned students are now working in Shanghai's
educational institutions, and they have become backbones in this
sector.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Haishan, an official of the Shanghai Municipal
Commission, said that in the 39 universities and colleges in the
city, more than 80 percent of the presidents and directors of
departments have been selected from among returned students.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than half of the returned students in the city
work in foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The returned students are also encouraged to set up their own
businesses. There are now 570 enterprises run by returned
students, with a total investment exceeding 100 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
