<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak President Cuts down Budget by One Third </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 14 (Xinhua) -- President Rafiq Tarar has asked
his staff to reduce expenditures of the Presidential House by one
third and returned 20 million rupees (450,000 U.S. dollars)
allocated for the Presidential House in the 1998-99 budget.
</P>
<P>
The steps, taken five months ago by Tarar after assuming his
Presidency, include reduction in the presidency staff,
entertainment expenditure, gift fund and personal expenditure,
according to a report Sunday by the News Network International, an
independent news agency in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted sources from the Presidential House as saying
that Tarar has reduced 60 percent of employees in the Public Wing
of the Presidential House.
</P>
<P>
He has also decided to use Falcon aircraft instead of Boeing
737 for his domestic tours.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that the number of employees in the Public and
Personal Wing of the Presidential House have been reduced to 584
from 980.
</P>
<P>
During the 1997-98 budget, an amount of 1.2 million rupees
(27,000 dollars) was allocated for presenting gifts to various
dignitaries. Former President Farooq Leghari had already consumed
half of the budget while President Tarar spent only 100,000 rupees
(2,270 dollars) and returned the rest of 500,000 rupees (11,350
dollars) to the government.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there is complete restriction on official daily
lunch, and serving of pastries and other refreshments with tea to
guests have also been banned, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
President Tarar has also removed lancers from the Presidential
House and electric lights remain off after office hours. For the
first time in Pakistan's history, the President and his staff
offered hadj on their own expenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
