<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- European Investment Bank has decided to grant Egypt
114 million U.S. dollars in loans for projects on dam construction
and drainage system innovation.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Ministry of Public Works and Water Resources and the
bank signed two agreements on the loans Saturday, the
Arabic-language daily Al Ahram reported here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The first loan of 75 million ecu (about 90 million dollars)
will be used for the building of Naga Hamadi dam, some 600
kilometers south of Cairo, to improve irrigation system and
generate electricity.
</P>
<P>
The second, 20 million ecu (about 24 million dollars), will go
to innovation of 16 irrigation and drainage stations in Beni Suef
and Minya governorates.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The Gulf Cooperation Council member states gained some
1.6 million dollars in 1997 from the 8 billion dollars worth of
imports from Japan due to the devaluation of about 20 percent in
yen from June 1997 to June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Arab daily Al Hayat reported that Saudi Arabia is the
biggest consumer of Japanese commodities, followed by the United
Arab Emirates and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The yen has slumped to an eight-year low of 144.70 against the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Iran signed a protocol on economic
cooperation Saturday, the first of its kind in 19 years.
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, the two countries would boost bilateral
trade and joint investments, facilitate exchange of information
and set up joint banks.
</P>
<P>
Iranian investments in Egypt are recorded at 85 million
dollars, and bilateral trade volume stands at 80 million dollars,
with Egyptian exports to Iran amounting to 35 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has signed a contract to import 300,000 tonnes
of wheat from France.
</P>
<P>
The 32-million-dollar contract brought the total wheat imports
from France to 1.3 million tonnes this year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt imports 4-5 million tonnes of wheat annually, with 95
percent coming from the U.S. originally.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili said that
Egypt would reach 75 percent of self-sufficiency in wheat by the
year 2000 as against the current 55 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
