<HEADLINE> Brunei to Set up Wildlife Rehabilitation Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Brunei will set up a
wildlife rehabilitation center to protect endangered species,
particularly wild orang utans (a kind of ape), according to a
press report here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The project, approved by the Brunei government, will be
situated at the Batang Duri Recreation Center in the eastern
Temburong District, one of the four districts of Brunei, Brunei's
leading newspaper Borneo Bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
Funds to establish and operate the center will be raised from
the private sector, it said.
</P>
<P>
The center is aimed at providing a refugee and rehabilitation
center for highly endangered species such as the wild orang utans
living in Borneo where Brunei is located, the report said.
</P>
<P>
An orang utan sanctuary and a school of animal behavior is also
included in the proposed center, with research facilities for
Bruneian and foreign universities to study animal behavior and the
rehabilitation process.
</P>
<P>
Permanent forest reserves and national parks where the release
of endangered species into the wild are also part of the project,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
