<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Frustrated with Israeli Intransigent Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
Sunday expressed frustration with Israel's intransigent policy,
which he said doomed the latest U.S. peace plan and plunged the
peace process to extreme danger.
</P>
<P>
"There is no hope that Israel accepts the American peace
initiative that calls on it to withdraw from over 13 percent of
the West Bank," Moussa said after a meeting here between President
Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the talks between the two leaders
centered on the Israeli attempt to "go around with and change" the
proposal to avoid making the stipulated withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the Israeli side only takes action to weaken,
minimize or trifle with the elements of the American initiative, a
matter the Palestinians do not accept," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that the peace process as a whole has come to a
halt and that Israel was taking very "grave" measures, including
the Jewish settlements, which mean the creation of militants, an
invitation to violence and the use of violence.
</P>
<P>
"Once you provide radical Israelis with weapons you cannot
blame the other side for defending themselves. This is very
dangerous and like playing with fire to the maximum," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Arafat has said more than once that enough is enough and that
the Palestinians cannot go any further because the situation is
really very dangerous," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
In this condition, the Egyptian diplomat said Mubarak will hold
contacts with a number of Arab leaders within the next few days to
raise the subject with them.
</P>
<P>
Asked if U.S. threats to wash its hands of the peace process
were serious, Moussa said that it was not in the U.S. interest to
do so, but it would be beneficial if Washington announces its
position.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone is extremely upset, but concerning the U.S. role as
the main sponsor of the peace process, we hope that it continues
as the honest broker," he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived early in the day in the latest of frequent
visits he made to Cairo since the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks
were bogged down 15 months ago over Israel's construction of
Jewish housing units in traditionally Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
