<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Right-Wing Party Objects Further Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 14 (Xinhua) -- A leading Israeli far-rightist
party reaffirmed its opposition to a major troop redeployment in
the West Bank which is reportedly being considered by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Yitzhak Levy, leader of the National Religious Party (NRP)
which is a major coalition partner, told Israel Radio that his
party's central committee will decide whether it will leave the
government if a 13 percent pullback for the second redeployment is
approved.
</P>
<P>
The NRP is a religious party that still embraces the ideology
of Greater Israel, a belief that Israel must retain control over
the land from the Mediterranean Sea to the Jordan River.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Likud-led coalition has only a slim majority of 61
seats in the 120-seat Knesset (Parliament), and the NRP, which has
nine Knesset seats, can easily bring down the government if it
votes with the opposition in future no-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
Under Israeli law, if more than 61 Knesset members vote
no-confidence against any government decision, the government must
step down to pave the way for new elections.
</P>
<P>
The NRP's spiritual mentor, Rabbi Mordechai Eliyahu, told
Netanyahu Saturday night that if a major second pullback is
carried out, he will try to persuade the NRP to pull out from the
government.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was insisting that neither the right nor the left
would unseat his government, saying that once he makes a decision
on the pullback, he could convince all coalition partners and the
public to support it.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is currently under increasing pressure from both the
Palestinians and the United States, which ask him to hand over 13
percent more of the West Bank in the second redeployment to revive
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
But the right-wingers within his government strongly oppose any
withdrawal of more than 9 percent, citing this will endanger the
security of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
