NANNING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Nine cities in southwest China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region are plagued by acid rain, a
recently released bulletin on the region's environmental situation
revealed.
</P>
<P>
The nine cities include this capital of the autonomous region,
Liuzhou, Guilin and Wuzhou. Most of these cities have
concentrations of industrial plants and consume large amounts of
coal each day.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the average pH (a measure of acidity
and alkalinity) of the air in these cities was 5.1 in 1997, a
decrease of 0.24 over the level in 1996, which reflects a
significant increase in acid level. Rainfall with a pH lower than
5.6 is regarded as acid rain in China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the nine cities also had more frequent
occurrences of acid rain last year, with an average rate of about
53 percent, 7.5 percentage points higher than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
High-sulfur coal fuel consumption, which constitutes 70 percent
of the region's energy consumption, is believed to be the main
cause of the aggravated acid rain situation, according to the
bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The acid rain situation has been getting worse and the area it
affects has been getting larger since the late 1980s, said Chen
Baiping, director of the supervision department of the Guangxi
Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Nanning has taken steps to tackle the problem since 1995, and
has succeeded in reducing the discharge of sulfur dioxide into the
air by over 10,000 tons each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
