<HEADLINE> Iran's Moderate Newspaper's Publisher Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The publisher of a moderate
newspaper Ali Mohammad Mahdavi Khorrami was released Sunday after
five days in detention, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Head of Tehran Judiciary Department Saeed Nobari said Khorrami,
managing director of Gozaresh-e Rouz (Daily Report), was released
on bail, adding that the investigation is continuing and the file
will go to court upon completion.
</P>
<P>
Khorrami was detained on June 9 soon after his newspaper was
banned for reprinting an article from an Arab publication claiming
Iranian government officials are transferring foreign capitals
abroad.
</P>
<P>
IRNA also quoted an informed source as saying that Gozaresh-e
Rouz's Editor-in-Chief Mohammad Aqazadeh was summoned by a court
immediately after Khorrami's release.
</P>
<P>
Gozaresh-e Rouz, a new and popular daily newspaper published by
IRNA's journalists, has come under fire of the conservatives in
recent weeks, who accused it of launching a pro-Western "cultural
campaign."
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, the license of another moderate newspaper
Jame'ah (Society) was also revoked by a court for publishing
"defamatory and untruthful articles."
</P>
<P>
But the newspaper is continuing publication pending a final
verdict from the appeal court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
