<HEADLINE> Cathay Pacific, Dragonair Take Part in HK New Airport Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 14 (Xinhua) -- One Cathay Pacific aircraft and
two from Dragonair took part in the final full-scale operational
trial of the new Hong Kong International Airport here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The new airport is scheduled to open on July 6 this year.
</P>
<P>
A newly-arrived Cathay Pacific Boeing 777-300 (HIB-HNH), which
is the longest commercial aircraft and the first such aircraft to
have been delivered in the world, touched down at the new airport
at Check Lap Kok to the north of the Lantau Island, at 11:35 a.m.
It stayed for about three hours, to be used to test such ground
services as baggage and cargo offloading, cabin-cleaning,
refueling and technical inspection facilities.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft returned to the existing Hong Kong airport at Kai
Tak at 2:50 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Two Dragonair's Airbus A320 aircraft made their first take-off
and landing at Chek Lap Kok. The two passenger airliners took off
from the Kai Tak airport and ferried over to land at Chek Lap Kok
without passengers onboard at 12:00 noon and 7:00 p.m., to
practice traffic control system as well as support operations
during the daytime and evening hours. Dragonair was the first
airline to practice evening take-off and landing at the airport.
</P>
<P>
A Federal Express cargo plane also participated in the trial by
landing at 1:00 p.m.
</P>
<P>
On May 2 this year, a Cathay Pacific's designer-painted
B747-200 aircraft named "The Spirit of Hong Kong" became the first
wide-bodied aircraft to land at Chek Lap Kok.
</P>
<P>
But it was a small aircraft of the Hong Kong Government Flying
Services (GFS) that became the first aircraft to land at the Chek
Lap Kok facility, on February 20 this year.
</P>
<P>
The airport is able to handle up to 35 million passengers and 3
million tons of cargo in its first 12 months of operation.
Ultimate design capacity is 87 million passengers and 9
million tons of cargo, making it one of the busiest airports in
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
