<HEADLINE> Israeli Woman Convicted of Failing to Prevent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 14 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli court Sunday
convicted 23-year-old Magret Harshefi of failing to prevent her
friend Yigal Amir from murdering former prime minister Yitzhak
Rabin in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Tel Aviv Magistrate Court ruled that Harshefi knew about
the intention of Amir, a fellow law student at Bar-Illan
University, to assassinate Rabin, but did nothing to stop him.
</P>
<P>
The court stressed that the ruling was based on Harshefi's own
testimony, which was given on her free will.
</P>
<P>
Court judges said there were contradictions in Harshefi's
testimony. On the one hand, she claimed that she viewed Amir's plan
as "fantasy" and did not take it seriously; on the other hand, she
made a call to Amir's home immediately after the news of the
murder was reported.
</P>
<P>
Harshefi will be sentenced in September and could face up to
two years in jail. Her attorney said she would probably appeal the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
The woman was acquitted of a second charge of aiding Amir in
his effort to obtain weapons illegally for use against the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Amir is serving a life sentence for murdering Rabin.
</P>
</TEXT>
