<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collection of Chinese Musical Relics Through 8,000 Years Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Bone flutes some 7,600 years old,
the oldest musical instruments unearthed in China, are included in
a 12-volume collection of musical relics, the first of its kind to
be published in China.
</P>
<P>
The famous 2,400-year-old Zenghouyi Chimes, unearthed in
Suixian County in central China's Hubei Province, representing the
advanced technology of casting bells in ancient China, are also
included in the collection along with other musical relics over a
8,000-year history.
</P>
<P>
The 12 volumes are the first in a 31-volume series. They
include nearly two million characters and over 5,000 photos and
pictures presenting Chinese musical relics from the New Stone Age
to the end of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), including actual
musical instruments, decorations on utensils, stone carvings,
paintings, sculptures and murals.
</P>
<P>
"The musical relics discovered in China have promoted the study
of Chinese musical development, and helped solve many puzzles in
Chinese musical history," said Wang Zichu, editor-in-chief of the
collection.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It used to be believed that the musical system of
seven scales was introduced to China from ancient Persia. However,
the 7,600-year-old bone flutes found in Wuyang County in central
China's Henan Province have seven holes in them, enabling the
player to master seven scales."
</P>
<P>
The compilation of the first 12 volumes of the collection, a
grand project initiated by the Academy of Arts of China, State
Cultural Relics Bureau and Institute of Archaeology under the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, has taken over ten years.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China has carried out a large-scale
investigation of its musical relics. Many relics included in the
collection are new discoveries, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
The other volumes in the series are expected to be published
within ten years, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
