<HEADLINE> Mubarak Promises to Mediate Eritrean-Ethiopian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has
promised to play a role in halting a major Ethiopia-Eritrea border
conflict, said Eritrea's foreign minister after his meeting with the
Egyptian leader Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
"President Mubarak promised to do his best and contact the
Ethiopian side in order to reach a ceasefire between the two
parties and to bring about a peaceful solution to Ethiopia-Eritrea
dispute," Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile Woldensae told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Woldensae, who arrived here Saturday night amid current efforts
to contain the bloody clashes, delivered a second message within a
week to Mubarak from Eritrean President Issayas Aferwerki.
</P>
<P>
An Eritrean delegation handed a message to Mubarak from
Aferwerki on Wednesday, asking Egypt and African countries to help
in resolving their country's border row with Ethiopia to head off
an explosion in the Horn of Africa. Hundreds of people have been
killed since the fightings broke out between the two former allies
on May 6.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the meeting which was also attended by Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, Woldensae said that Eritrea has
accepted Mubarak's initiative to settle its dispute with Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Woldensae's visit came on the heels of one paid to Cairo by
Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea accused each other of incursions. Hopes
that U.S.-led mediation would prevent a deterioration were dashed
last weekend as far bloodier clash had occurred.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader had sent two messages to leaders of both
countries, calling for an immediate end to fighting and urging
negotiations to resolve the border row that centers on a 400
square kilometers rocky triangle of land along their western
border.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of African Unity decided Saturday to send four
African presidents, of Burkina Faso, Djibouti, Zimbabwe and
Rwanda, to Ethiopia and Eritrea next week in a new initiative
aimed at ending the confrontations.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea and Ethiopia, among the world's poorest, are at odds
over at least six areas along their common border. Eritrea gained
independence from Ethiopia in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
