<HEADLINE> Unilever to Base China Group in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Unilever, a multinational
consumer goods company, plans to shore up its presence in China
with some major restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The Anglo-Dutch consumer goods company announced in May that it
intends to create a China Group in Shanghai to manage and
coordinate its long-term investment on the Chinese mainland, the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Niall FitzGerald and Morris Tabaksblat, two of Unilever's
chairmen, held a board meeting with five members of their global
team in Shanghai -- the first time that the Unilever board has
ever met outside Britain or the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Niall FitzGerald said this fully demonstrates his company's
confidence in China's vast market potential and its determination
to undertake long-term business development in the country.
</P>
<P>
Unilever first came to China in 1923, when it set up a
soap factory in China. In 1980, after China opened up its markets,
Unilever returned. It established its first modern joint venture
in Shanghai in 1986, manufacturing and selling Lux soap.
</P>
<P>
Unilever has so far invested 640 million US dollars in China,
and has set up 12 joint ventures across the country since 1986.
The company employs 6,000 workers in China.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 Unilever's turnover was 49.7 billion US dollars
globally, and its operating profit was 3.9 billion US dollars. The
company's sales in China hit 3.9 billion yuan (about 469 million
US dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Unilever's products range from cleaning products and personal
care items to specialty chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The company's has established a joint research center in
Shanghai with the Shanghai Institute of Organic Chemistry to
produce cosmetics and detergents using traditional Chinese
medicinal herbs, as well as setting up a 600,000-US dollar
scientific research fund together with the Shanghai Municipal
Commission of Science and Technology to promote basic research and
localization of Unilever products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
