<HEADLINE> WHO Helps South-East Asian Countries to Achieve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) is helping 10 countries in South-East Asia including Sri
Lanka to achieve the goal of better health for all people in the
spirit of inter-country cooperation and regional solidarity.
</P>
<P>
A WHO spokesman here Sunday said that the ten countries are
Bangladesh, Bhutan, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea,
India, Indonesia, Maldives, Myanmar, Nepal, Sri Lanka and
Thailand, which account for nearly a quarter of the world's
population.
</P>
<P>
One of several formidable health challenges face these
countries is Malaria, which threatens over 1,180 million people.
Hiv/Aids with over 2.6 million cases is also emerging as a major
public health problem in these countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, environmental degradation and changes in
life-styles have become priority areas requiring particular
attention in future health development in the region, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The WHO's net regular budget for activities in the region for
1998-99 is 96.24 million U.S. dollars, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
