<HEADLINE> Ramos to Accept UNESCO peace award in Senegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
will leave here Monday for a four-day official visit to Senegal to
receive the 1997 Felix Houphouet-Boigny Peace Award of the United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
(UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
In receiving the award in Dakar Thursday, the President will be
the first Asian head of state to receive the Peace Prize, awarded
annually since 1991 by UNESCO to honor persons who have
distinguished themselves in the preservation or restoration of
peace.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos and Chairman Nur Misuari of the Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF) will receive the prize from UNESCO
Director-General Federico Mayor and Nobel Peace laureate Henry
Kissinger at a ceremony in Dakar, Senegal.
</P>
<P>
Ramos and Misuari were the unanimous choice for this year's
Felix Houphouet-Boigny Peace Prize for the Peace Agreement that
was signed on September 2, 1996 that formally ended 27 years of
conflict in Mindanao, the Southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Ramos will share with Misuari the 800,000 Franc prize (133,000
U.S. dollars), peace diploma and gold medal that goes with the
award.
</P>
<P>
Previous recipients of the prestigious award include King Juan
Carlos of Spain and former U.S. President Jimmy Carter; Former
Prime Ministers Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres of Israel and
Chairman Yasser Arafat of the Palestinian Liberation Organization.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
