<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Satisfied with Start of World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 14 (Xinhua) -- As more goals scored, big crowds
turned up, few signs of Hooliganism around the stadiums and on
the stands, and clean and neat play put up by players in the first
four days of the World Cup, World governing body of Soccer FIFA is
quite satisfied with the start of France'98.
</P>
<P>
A total of 26 goals have been scored in the first 10 games, only
three red cards have been shown in the matches and the crowds have
behaved themselves in the sold-out stadiums.
</P>
<P>
"We are very happy with the pace of scoring and the attacking
spirit," said Keith Cooper, spokesman for FIFA.
</P>
<P>
Cooper said FIFA's compaigne against tackle from behind had
worked well:"People express surprise at the lack of red cards, but
it doesn't surprise us at all. We have merely created an
opportunity for players to play football without the possibility of
being tackled from behind. We're very happy that it's working."
</P>
<P>
Cooper was also satisfied with the crowd control measures taken
by the organisers:"This is truly an extension of four years ago in
the United States, and this is exactly what we wanted," Cooper said,
"The atmosphere creates it. The more joyful games you have, the
more joyful games there will be. It builds upon itself." 
</P>
</TEXT>
