<HEADLINE> Feature: Integrated Trial Preludes Opening of HK New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Passengers were checking in,
planes were landing, and cargoes were unloaded at the new Hong
Kong International Airport Sunday. It looked as if the airport is
in normal, full operation.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest and most integrated trial operation of the
new airport's airfield, passenger terminal and airport railway
links. The grand rehearsal preluded the opening of the airport,
scheduled for July 6.
</P>
<P>
Everything was "real" in the trial. From eight o'clock in the
morning, "passengers" -- men, women and children carrying big and
small pieces of luggage -- kept arriving and going through the
"in-town check-in" formalities at a downtown train station linked
to the new airport.
</P>
<P>
Other "passengers" traveled to the airport by bus, tour coach,
hotel limousine and private car.
</P>
<P>
After some 20 minutes ride by the Airport Express to Chek Lap
Kok, where the airport is located, the "passengers" were directed
to different terminals by a huge electronic board showing the
"flights" -- to London, Tokyo, Beijing and other cities.
</P>
<P>
A Cathay Pacific aircraft landed around 11:30 a.m., followed by
 the landing of a passenger flight of local airline Dragonair for
boarding at around 12:30 and a Federal Express cargo plane at 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
The day's trial involved some 15,000 people -- 12,000 volunteer
 "passengers" and "greeters" and 3,000 airport staff.
</P>
<P>
Clinton Leeks, corporate development director of the Airport
Authority, told reporters at the Fedex cargo unloading spot that
the airport was in full operation during the trial. He said even
the security system was put in place this time.
</P>
<P>
Leeks said the whole system had been "working well" although
the overall feedback would not be available until Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of some sections of the airport structure which are
still under construction, the official said there are "no big
problems" or "crucial items" remaining before the opening on July
6 and most parts of the airport are ready for service.
</P>
<P>
He said the Airport Authority has taken into consideration the
responses of previous trials in conducting this operation.
</P>
<P>
The new airport construction site is situated at the scenery
Chek Lap Kok Island, off the northern coast of Lantau Island, 25
kilometers west of Hong Kong's central business district.
</P>
<P>
The airport is able to handle up to 35 million passengers and 3
 million tons of cargo in its first 12 months of
operation. Ultimate design capacity will be 87 million passengers
and 9 million tons of cargo, making it one of the busiest
airports in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
