<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges U.S. to Smoothen Technology Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- China hopes the United States will
do more to remove artificial barriers to its technology exports
and financial credits to China so that their trade imbalance could
be corrected.
</P>
<P>
The hope was voiced by Li Zhaoxing, Chinese Ambassador to the U.S.,
in a recent interview with the official Chinese weekly magazine
Outlook, which will be published on June 15.
</P>
<P>
Li also hoped the U.S. side to further enhance the
competitiveness of its products on the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Although statistics released by the two sides are not exactly
the same, they all show that the two-way trade has grown at an
annual average rate of more than 18 percent since 1979, the
Chinese ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
In the case of the U.S., its direct exports to China have
created more than 300,000 jobs at home and the bilateral trade
provided at least one million jobs for its industrial and service
sectors, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the Sino-U.S. trade, China remained in the deficit
throughout the 1979-1992 period and only moved to surplus as late
as in 1993, Li noted.
</P>
<P>
As for the size of China's surplus against the U.S., Li said
that there is a great difference between the statistics of the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Citing the 1996 trade statistics from the Chinese customs, Li
said that China's surplus in that year was only 10.53 billion
dollars. But the statistics of the U.S. commerce department
indicated a surplus as high as 39.52 billion dollars, a figure
definitely exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
There are many reasons for this difference, he said, adding
that at least the added value of the re-exports from Hong Kong and
exports by Sino-U.S. joint ventures in China are involved.
</P>
<P>
Sino-U.S. trade and economic relations, however, are basically
complementary rather than competitive, the Chinese ambassador
stressed.
</P>
<P>
China's exports to the U.S. are mainly textiles, footwear, toys
and other labor-intensive products with low added values, which
are rarely manufactured in the U.S. and have no influence on its
employment, he said. On the contrary, they benefit the U.S. retail
trade and consumers.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. exports to China are largely technology-intensive,
such as planes, machinery, electronics and communication products,
he said.
</P>
<P>
With its economic development, China is both willing and
capable to increase imports from the U.S., Li said.
</P>
<P>
In the three years from now, he said, China's imports are
expected to hit 600 billion dollars, which will represents a very
good opportunity for U.S. exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
