<HEADLINE> Colombia More Concerned about Giving Top Form </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LYON, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Colombia coach Hernan Dario Gomez, whose
team will face Romania in Group G opener here on Monday says he is
more concerned that his players give 100 percent than suffering a
loss.
</P>
<P>
What Gomez put his team through on Saturday was a punishing
120-minute training session at their base 50 kilometers south of Lyon.
</P>
<P>
Striker Faustino Asprilla left the pitch with his right leg
strapped in ice but he was expected fit for the game.
</P>
<P>
The Parma player has amazing dribbling skill and killer instinct
before the goal and is Colombia's major scoring hope.
</P>
<P>
Midfielder Carlos Valderrama, the veteran with distinctive organge
haristyle playing his third World Cup, said Colombia would face a
tough game in their first appearance in Group G.
</P>
<P>
"Whoever has the goal-scoring opportunities has to take advantage
of them and we hope they'll be in our favor. We're confident that
we'll product a positive result."
</P>
<P>
Valderrama, who refused to give any predictions, added that "It
will be a very good game because we are facing a rival that plays very
well."
</P>
<P>
It is also a rival that is aging, which Romanian coach Anghel
Iordanescu worries most.
</P>
<P>
Gheorghe Hagi, Gheorghe Popescu and Bogdan Stelea are now over 30
and seeing their vision, stamina and physical strength dwindling.
</P>
<P>
Iordanescu, however, is confident that their experience would make
it up.
</P>
<P>
"Only an experienced team will be able to get through the group in
France. We're talking about strong opponents like Colombia, England
and Tunisia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Several of players at the 1994 World Cup in the United States will
be back in France, he added, and will relish their last chance to play
in the world's top soccer tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
