<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Lebanon Criticize Israeli Policy in Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Lebanon have criticized
Israel for putting hurdles in the Middle East peace process, the
Voice of Arabs radio reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Cairo-based radio, Jordanian Prime
Minister Abdul-Salam Majali blamed Israel for obstructing the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinian cause, including establishing an
independent state with Jerusalem as the capital, has won worldwide
support as a result of the "rational stance" adopted by the Arabs
in advancing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, Israel's closest ally in the Arab world, has recently
been criticizing the intransigence and hardline policy of the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
In another interview with the radio, Lebanese Defense Minister
Mohsen Dalloul accused Israel of cheating at the peace process
while the Arabs are working to rescue it.
</P>
<P>
Dalloul affirmed his country's efforts to seek a just and
comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
He lambasted an Israeli proposal to withdraw from south Lebanon
conditionally, calling it a "deceitful" policy aimed at separating
Lebanon from Syria in their peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel decided to endorse the United Nations
Security Council Resolution 425, which calls for a unilateral
withdrawal from Lebanon. But it called on the Lebanese government
to negotiate security arrangements for border areas before it
pulls back troops from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which agree to coordinate their stances on
key issues, have rejected the proposal. They insist that the
withdrawal be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants the return of the Golan Heights, which Israel
captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is ready to resume peace talks with Israel provided
that the negotiations are picked up from where they have been left
off, Dalloul said.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon to allegedly protect its northern areas from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese Muslim guerrilla groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
