<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Cancels Reporters' Visit to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran has canceled a visit by a
group of reporters to the United States after conservatives'
protests, the Farda (Tomorrow) daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Iranian Ministry of Culture and Islamic
Guidance Issa Saharkhiz was quoted by the daily as saying that one
reason for the cancellation is that the visit is politicized after
the American side arranged for the Iranian reporters an interview
with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department has reportedly confirmed that
Albright has agreed to an interview with the Iranian reporters.
</P>
<P>
The American Institute of the Middle East Insight has invited
the Iranian journalists to attend a seminar under the title "Iran,
the U.S. and the Middle East Issues," which is scheduled to
open on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The planned trip to the U.S. by the Iranian reporters has been
severely criticized by the conservatives, who believe that the
interview with Albright would not serve the interests of Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran's plan to dispatch journalists to the U.S. came after the
visits to Iran by several American cultural and scientific
delegations following Iranian President Mohammad Khatami's call in
January for cultural dialog between the two peoples in a bid to
break their "wall of mistrust."
</P>
<P>
Washington has been pursuing containment policy against Tehran
since the Islamic Revolution in Iran in 1979. It broke up
diplomatic ties with Iran after radical Iranian students occupied
the U.S. Embassy in Iran and took staffers hostages in 1980.
</P>
</TEXT>
