<HEADLINE> Saudi Linguist Develops Speech Synthesizer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 14 (Xinhua) -- A Saudi linguist has
developed the prototype of a speech synthesizer that can
communicate in 11 languages, while using Arabic as the base
language, according to reports reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Al-Humeidan, dean of the Colleges of Languages and
Translation at King Saud University, said the computer, which is
attached to a fax machine, also responds to questions in 11
languages, and can turn on the fax machine if instructed to do
so.
</P>
<P>
The languages include English, French, German, Spanish,
Italian, Russian, Hebrew, Persian, Japanese and Urdu, Al-Humeidan
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that one of the priorities of his college is to
promote Arabization of scientific and medical terminology.
</P>
<P>
"No nation has developed by learning in languages other than
its own," he said. 
</P>
