<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 07:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Transmitter in Kuwait to Face Sentence, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 14 (Xinhua) -- An AIDS virus carrier who
intentionally transmits the deadly virus to another person in
Kuwait will face a sentence and a fine, the Arab Times newspaper
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Convener of the Kuwaiti National Committee for Fighting AIDS
Hind Al-Shoumer was quoted by the paper as saying that the
offender will be sentenced to seven years' imprisonment and fined
23,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shoumer said that AIDS, or acquired immunodeficiency
syndrome, is a deadly infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
Under Kuwaiti laws, health departments are empowered to enforce
testing on people who are suspected of carrying AIDS virus even if
they refuse to take the tests.
</P>
<P>
And the health departments are obliged to inform the other
spouse about the disease after detecting the AIDS virus in any
spouse.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shoumer said AIDS patients would be allowed to receive
treatment overseas under the condition that they tell the health
departments upon their return to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry would deport an AIDS virus carrier should
the health minister so ordain, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
