<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> STD Cases Decrease in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Cases of sexually-transmitted
diseases (STD) in Zimbabwe went down over the past year although
the figure still remains high, according to a senior health
official.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with the Sunday Mail, Manager of the
National Sexually-transmitted Infection Control Program, Owen
Mugurungi said that the STD cases reported in all government
hospitals and clinics last year were 814,032 against 838,697 at
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The actual number could be even higher since the figure did
not take into account the people treated in private clinics and
hospitals, according to Mugurungi.
</P>
<P>
Mugurungi said although the figures had stabilized between
800,000 and 900,000 cases a year from 1994 to 1997, they were
still too high and his organization's immediate task is to reduce
the cases to 100,000 cases a year.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that 92 percent of all people with STD who were
tested for HIV infection were positive.
</P>
<P>
About 96 percent of HIV transmission was done through sexual
intercourse and STD continued to be a major contributor to
HIV/AIDS cases, with the sexually-active 15 to 45 years age group
constituting more than 50 percent of the total cases reported.
</P>
<P>
Mugurungi said that the STD cases ranked among the top five
causes of out-patient hospital and clinic attendances, and top
four lifestyle illnesses, which included alcohol, tobacco and
accidents.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization revealed that an estimated 333
million new cases of curable STDs were recorded worldwide every
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
