<HEADLINE> Iranian Interior Minister Ready to Face </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran's moderate Interior Minister
Abdollah Nouri has announced his readiness to face the challenge
of impeachment raised by a group of conservative Majlis
(parliament) deputies, an Iranian daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm preparing myself for the response to the objections
raised by the deputies against my conduct as a minister," Nouri
said in a letter to Majlis Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
He said that "I need to use the time law permits me for the
preparation of my case," the pro-moderate daily Iran News reported.
</P>
<P>
A total of 31 Majlis deputies on Wednesday demanded an
impeachment of the interior minister, accusing him of creating
tension in the society, making provocative statements, issuing
permits for demonstrations which ended in violence and appointing
inexperienced people to managerial posts at the ministry.
</P>
<P>
According to the Majlis regulations, Nouri should stand in
front his challengers within 10 days. It is believed that the
Majlis would hold a hot debate over Nouri's fate on Sunday since
Friday and Saturday are holidays for the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted an informed source close to President
Mohammad Khatami as saying that the president would attend the
Majlis session personally. Khatami showed his strong support for
his interior minister soon after the impeachment was raised.
</P>
<P>
Khatami termed Nouri as a "capable and outstanding personality
of the Islamic system," saying that he believed Nouri has the
necessary capability to elaborate on the stance and issues
related to the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The impeachment of the interior minister, one of the pillars of
Khatami's government, was believed to be another step launched by
the conservatives against the moderate president and his
government, after Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi, Khatami's
another strong supporter, was put on trial on corrupt charges last
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
