<HEADLINE> Uganda Hails UN Move for Rescuing Abducted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
hailed the move taken by the United Nations Representative for
Children in Armed Conflicts, Olara Otunnu, to rescue
Ugandan children abducted into Sudan by rebels of the Lord
Resistance Forces (LRA).
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government encourages the U.N. move in this
direction, the New Vision newspaper Sunday quoted David Pulkol,
the Director-General of External Security Organization, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Government encourages all those who can contribute to help
release those innocent youths," Pulkol said. "Otunnu is
privileged to try to end the suffering of these children as he
does to other children all over the world."
</P>
<P>
Otunnu, a former Ugandan Minister of Foreign Affairs, is
reported to hold talks with all parties concerned in order to
halt the involvement of children in the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. figures, there have been 8,000 to 10,000
children kidnaped from northern Uganda by LRA rebels spearheaded
by Joseph Kony.
</P>
<P>
Some 800 LRA rebels recently stole into the northern districts
of Gulu and Kitgum.
</P>
<P>
They abducted villagers and used land mines to loot goods from
vehicles on main roads.
</P>
<P>
To curb the rampant rebel activities, the government deployed
heavy military presence in the north.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Ugandan government has decided to increase its
defense spending by 26 percent in its new budget in a fresh
counter-attack against the rebels. 
</P>
