<HEADLINE> Lebanese Vote in Final Round of Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese in the eastern province of
Bekaa Sunday began voting in the fourth and final round of the
first municipal and mayoral elections in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese army tightened the security measures in key
intersections and around polling stations in order to avoid riot
or violence related to the polls.
</P>
<P>
An Interior Ministry statement said no serious security
problems were reported in the previous rounds of elections, except
some minor fist scuffles which had led to the arrest of more than
150 people.
</P>
<P>
The polls started at 7:00 a.m. (4:00 a.m. GMT) and will close
at 5:00 p.m. (2:00 p.m. GMT) and counting of votes will be
finished late Monday.
</P>
<P>
The fiercest race in the polls is expected in the provincial
capital of Zahleh, the largest Catholic-inhabited city of the
Middle East, between candidates backed by President Elias Hrawi, a
Maronite Catholic, and those backed by his elder son George Hrawi
and Greek Catholic parliament member Elie Skaff.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, which
spearheads a guerrilla war to oust Israel from an occupied
enclave in south Lebanon, will confront a formidable coalition of
Amal movement, headed by House Speaker Nabih Berri, and the
National Syrian Socialist Party and the Communist party.
</P>
<P>
They will compete for the control of the ancient city of
Baalbek, the one time major tourist attraction of pre-civil war
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah and Islamic Coalition, the nation's largest Sunni
militant faction, and the outlawed Lebanese Forces, the
Christians' main militia during the 1975-1990 civil war, were the
three major winners in the past three rounds of elections which
were held on four consecutive Sundays starting from May 24.
</P>
<P>
A total of 7,662 members for 646 municipal councils, and 2,041
mayors and chiefs in 1,282 towns and villages will be finally
elected in the polls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
