<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primary Education Week Begins in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's national primary
education week began Sunday, with a view to increasing
mass-awareness on education.
</P>
<P>
Activities such as children conferences, rallies,
tree-plantation were organized in each primary school in all the
64 districts of the country on the inaugural day.
</P>
<P>
Important road islands, primary education offices and all
primary schools in the capital city of Dhaka had also been
decorated with colorful banners and posters on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the compulsory union and sub-district compulsory
primary education committees would hold separate meetings in this
regard at their respective areas during the week.
</P>
<P>
President Shahabuddin Ahmed and Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
issued messages on the eve of the week.
</P>
<P>
"There is no alternative to attaining universal primary
education in building the next generation as the able citizens of
the country," the president said in his message.
</P>
<P>
Universal primary education "is also necessary in bringing
nearly half of the total (127 million) population under literacy
program," he added.
</P>
<P>
In her message, Prime Minister Hasina called upon all
irrespective of caste, creed and political affiliation to spread
primary education among the people of all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
Eradication of illiteracy was the foremost task to secure a
seat of dignity for the country in the world map, she stressed.
This "is our constitutional obligation."
</P>
<P>
Due to relentless efforts of the government over the last two
years, the rate of literacy in the country had stood at 51
percent, she stated.
</P>
<P>
"If we can continue our efforts, in the next few years, we
would be able to free the country from the curse of illiteracy,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina announced in March this year that the government had
adopted an education program aiming to eradicate illiteracy in the
country by the year 2006. 
</P>
</TEXT>
