<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Continue Advancing Northwards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, 14 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's government troops continued
advancing northwards from their earlier held positions in general
area Mankulam in the Northern province of the country, a military
spokesman here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said the troops were supported effectively by artillery and
aircraft of the Sri Lankan Air Force.
</P>
<P>
Tamil rebels launched three physical counterattacks with rocket
propelled grenades, machine guns and small arms.
</P>
<P>
The troops repulsed the counterattacks effectively with armor
causing heavy casualties among the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Fighting lasted for about four hours. However, the spokesman
gave no casualties and other details.
</P>
<P>
Troops' artillery continued to engage the rebel targets in
depth adding to terrorist casualties, he added.
</P>
<P>
The fierce fighting took place after the troops continued their
advance to recapture the strategic Mankulam town on its way to
clear a 75-km route between the North and the South launched in
May last year.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a war against the
government for a separate state in the north and east of the
country since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
