<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to List More Firms Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- China will list more enterprises
on overseas market, while considering ways to attract more foreign
investors to the country's B share market, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China will deepen its security reform and enhance
supervision to ensure the healthy development of the security
industry, which is expected to play an active role in fulfilling
the country's goal of 8-percent economic growth this year,
said the newspaper quoting a top securities official.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Zhengqing, chairman of China Securities Regulatory
Commission(CSRC), said that China will stick to its policies of
raising funds through international capital market despite
negative impacts of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis has brought both challenges and opportunities,"
Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that China has started to select a fifth batch of
firms for overseas listing and will issue the list in the near
future. The sixth batch of candidate firms should be published
before the year end, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country will expand selection to allow more
large enterprises with good profits, advanced management and
strong development potential to be listed abroad.
</P>
<P>
He added that overseas listings will mainly concentrate on the
Hong Kong Market. Although the market plunged this week, he said
he is confident that Hong Kong market will rebound in the future.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that China will also select some good enterprises to
be listed on both the New York Stock Exchange and the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
So far, 43 enterprises have been listed on overseas markets,
collecting more than 10 billion dollars for Chinese state-owned
enterprises, and enhancing the status of Hong Kong as an
international financial center.
</P>
<P>
Expressing serious concern over the bearish mood in B share
trading, Zhou said that CSRC will consider taking measures to
activate B share market, such as perfect pre-selection rules,
examination and approval standards and supervision regulations.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has just started drafting regulations for
establishment of Sino-foreign securities funds.
</P>
<P>
Zhou noted that CSRC will concentrate on establishing an
effective risk-control system over the securities market, and push
for an enhanced legal framework for the securities system this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
