<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir: Foreign Investors Refrain From Exerting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia welcomes foreign
investments but refuses to allow investors to use their economic
power to exert political influence in the country, Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that foreign investors were welcomed to the
country and make honest profits from their ventures but they
should refrain from exerting political influence.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want foreign investors to come to gain benefits only
for themselves and even prepare to play a role in determining the
leadership and other issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was not the business of the foreign investors to do so, said
Mahathir when launching a national youth's carnival to raise money
for the National Special Fund at the Independent Square here.
</P>
<P>
He said that the people in the country were capable of
determining their own leaders and managing their country
politically.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that Malaysia was peaceful and
prosperous due to the efforts by the people in the country and not
only because of foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "Our own people could also help to assist the
country and this could be seen today when they respond to the call
by the government and strive to free themselves from pressures to
import goods by producing items for the domestic market, heading
for local tourist destinations and buying local products."
</P>
<P>
"We will manage our economy so that we will remain free and our
independence will not be affected," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that it was the responsibility of all Malaysians
to ensure the sovereignty and independence of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
