<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Lifts Import Curbs on Sri Lankan Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- India has lifted curbs on the
import of 106 Sri Lankan products under the Open General License
enabling South Asian nations to export these without any licensing
or other Non-Tariff Barriers, the Indian High Commission sources
here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
These products cover desiccated coconut, cloves, pepper,
cassia, cinnamon barks, lower value range brooms, arecanut,
nutmeg, mace and other vegetable matter, most of which are
traditional exports from Sri Lanka to India.
</P>
<P>
India's policy is in response to Sri Lanka's request for a
liberalized trade regime, the sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
They added through this policy, India has fulfilled its
commitment to Sri Lanka made during the third session of the
Indo-Lanka Joint Commission in 1997, to open its market for Sri
Lanka and thus address the concerns about the balance of trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
