<HEADLINE> Iceland Backs Lithuania's Bid for NATO Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Iceland President Olofur
R. Grimsson, on a three-day visit to Lithuania, voiced his support
for Lithuania's bid for a NATO membership on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in Vilnius, Lithuania, at a joint
press conference with his Lithuanian counterpart Valdas Adamkus.
</P>
<P>
Grimsson said that as a member state of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization, Iceland backs the organization's eastward
expansion and holds that NATO membership should be available to
every nation.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania takes its efforts to join NATO as its major
diplomatic goal, said Adamkus.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions about Russia's proposal to build up
European security based on the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), Adamkus said such regional security
organization alone can not guarantee Europe's security.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, the two presidents also discussed
bilateral cooperation in trade, science and culture. They signed
an agreement on avoiding double taxation.
</P>
<P>
Grimsson arrived in Vilnius, the capital of Lithuania, on
Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
