<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Asks Americans to Share Country with Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Saturday called on Americans to share the country with immigrants
and accept that in the coming century there will be no majority
race in the nation.
</P>
<P>
"We should share our country with immigrants, not shun them or
shut them out," the Associated Press quoted the president as
saying in a commencement address Saturday to the graduating class
of Portland State University, Oregon.
</P>
<P>
However, "Unless we handle this well, immigration of this sweep
and scope can threaten the bonds of our union," he told about
3,000 graduates, of which 5 percent are citizens of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Immigrants must do their part to be full citizens, Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's remarks highlighted an emerging theme of his
second-term agenda: persuading Americans that ethnic and cultural
diversity can be a strength for this country, and that America
should set an example for the world, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Ethnic pride is a very good thing," he said. "But pride in
one's ethnic and racial heritage must never become an excuse to
withdraw from the larger American community. That does not honor
diversity, it breeds divisiveness. And that could weaken America."
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Clinton said immigrants represent the spirit
that built this country: a drive to succeed, a commitment to
family, a hope for a better life.
</P>
<P>
But some Americans wrongly see immigrants as a threat, he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the nation is in the midst of a new wave of
immigration that is the largest in a century, and more diverse
than any in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
"Today, largely because of immigration, there is no majority
race in Hawaii or Houston or New York City," he said. Within five
years, he added, there will be no majority race in California, the
most populous state in the country.
</P>
<P>
"And in a little more than 50 years, there will be no majority
race in the United States," Clinton said. "No other nation in
history has gone through demographic change of this magnitude,
over so short a time. It can either strengthen and unite America
or weaken and divide us. We must decide."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
