<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Helps Child Offenders Begin New Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has launched a program
to speed up the rehabilitation of convicted child offenders,
Sunday's Bangkok Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, convicted child offenders will be given
specialist rehabilitation in an effort to turn them away from
crime.
</P>
<P>
Youngsters committing minor crimes will be sent home but will
be told to regularly report to social workers.
</P>
<P>
More serious juvenile criminals will be dealt with on a
case-by-case basis. And those guilty of robbery or rape and other
serious crimes, including repeated offenses, will be sent to a
special rehabilitation center.
</P>
<P>
Vicha Mahakun, deputy chief justice of the Central Juvenile and
Family Court, was quoted as saying that splitting up the juveniles
would prevent them from being influenced by their peers.
</P>
<P>
In the past, juvenile criminals were sent home regardless of
their crimes or their age.
</P>
<P>
The program advocates a more humane approach when juveniles are
sent home. Staff and warders would be taught to handle them more
gently and improve their living conditions.
</P>
<P>
Adisai Ahapanun, a senior social worker with the Justice
Ministry, said the aim was to change the attitude of staff so that
they viewed juveniles not as "young criminals".
</P>
<P>
Visa Benjamano, director of the Child Welfare Protection
Division of the Labor and Social Welfare Ministry, suggested that
the ministry train staff to work as social workers and
psychologists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
