<HEADLINE> Bombay Stock Index Experiences Ups and Downs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The sensitive index on the
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market during the week experienced ups
and downs when it started weak at 3,416.73 points but recovered to
3,468.07 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday it reacted sharply to touch 3,311.41, but at the
fag-end it recovered once again to close at 3,347.40, still
showing an increased fall of 70.49 points from last week's mark of
3,417.89.
</P>
<P>
The national index fell by 43.15 points to close at 1,470.79
from 1,513.94, while the BSE-200 index dropped by 10.68 points to
334.10 and BSE us dollar index lost 4.3 points at 132.50.
</P>
<P>
Despite aggressive buying by foreign institutional investors,
equities opened sharply lower on reports that Duff &AMP; Phelps had
downgraded its outlook on Indian sovereign credit rating from
stable to negative in the light of the fiscal slippage and
deterioration in the balance of payment.
</P>
<P>
Again on Wednesday the market suffered severely on heavy bull
liquidation coupled with renewed selling by foreign institutional
investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
