<HEADLINE> Baht Stable Despite Yen's Plunge: Bank Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Chatumongol Sonakul, governor of
Thailand's central bank, has said the baht remained relatively
stable with no signs of speculative activity despite the week-long
continued fall of the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The yen reached an eight-year low last Friday, testing 145 to
the dollar before strengthening late in the day to end at 144.5.
</P>
<P>
The baht was traded late Friday at 43.37/47 to the dollar,
compared with 43.12 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed Friday's slide in regional currencies and
equities markets to the release of Japanese economic figures which
showed that the country is officially in a recession.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese gross domestic product (GDP) shrank 1.3 percent in
the first quarter, the second consecutive quarter's fall, the
internationally recognized definition of recession.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said the baht held fairly steady against the dollar
and trading activity was normal although the yen continued to
slide.
</P>
<P>
Regulators were closely monitoring trading activity in the
foreign exchange markets and were prepared to take action to deter
speculation, said Chatumongol, quoted by a TV report Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) Friday closed down 4.55
points at 279.37 on thin trade worth 1.1 billion baht (26 million
dollars). The market posted losses for six days in a row, with the
SET index now at an 11-year low. 
</P>
</TEXT>
