<HEADLINE> Thai Ruling Party Denies Early Election Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior leader of the Thai
Democrat Party, which leads the coalition government, has denied
reports that an early election would soon be held because of the
government's inability to handle the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said earlier that Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai,
under fierce attack by the opposition, was about to dissolve
parliament and hold an early election soon.
</P>
<P>
Democrat Party deputy chairman Banyat Bantadtan said in remarks
published Sunday by Bangkok Post that such reports were merely
rumors.
</P>
<P>
He told a party seminar of local leaders in Kuandon district in
Bangkok that the Democrat Party was merely preparing itself for a
possible early election.
</P>
<P>
"Although we are holding training sessions and seminars on the
election, this is only part of our on-going preparations," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He added: "Don't panic and think there will be a general
election within the next month or two. The prime minister has
stated clearly that the government... wants time to tackle the
economy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
