<HEADLINE> HKSAR Chief Executive Arrives in Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China arrived in
Sydney Sunday morning to start his first official visit to the
city and Melbourne, the two biggest business, industrial and
cultural centers of Australia.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive will meet with political and business
leaders in Australia, including Australian Prime Minister John
Howard, premiers of the New South Wales and Victoria states,
Australia's two most important states, and senior business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Tung will promote stronger business links between Hong Kong and
Australia and seek more travel convenience for Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) passport holders, the Information
Services Department of the HKSAR government said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive will also discuss continued cooperation in
trade liberalization and the use and development of information
technology.
</P>
<P>
He will deliver three keynote speeches in Sydney and Melbourne
at which he is expected to touch on the East Asian financial
crisis, Hong Kong's first year as a Special Administrative Region
and the successful implementation of the "One Country, Two System"
concept, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Tung will meet with Hong Kong community representatives Sunday
in Sydney and address the influential Asia Australia Institute.
</P>
<P>
He will call on New South Wales Premier Bob Carr Monday, and
fly to Melbourne Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Tung will meet with Australian Prime Minister John
Howard, Deputy Prime Minister and Trade Minister Tim Fischer,
Finance Minister John Fahey and Victorian Premier Jeff Kennett.
</P>
<P>
Tung will conclude his visit to Australia Wednesday and fly
from Melbourne to Auckland for a three-day visit to New Zealand.
</P>
</TEXT>
