<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Rejects G-8 Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- India termed the reference to
Indo-Pakistan disputes in the joint communique of the Group Eight
countries as coercive and intrusive, and regretted that the G-8
decided to block fresh loans to India.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the External Affairs Ministry said Saturday
night that India can not consider any prescriptions which had the
effect of undermining its independent decision-making.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman complained that major industrialized countries
did not respond to India's "positive gesture" made in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he said, the G-8 foreign ministers repeated
unrealistic prescriptions couched in the language of pressure in
London.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out third party involvement of any kind whatsoever in
India-Pakistan talks, claiming that India remained committed to
developing a framework of peaceful relations with Pakistan through
a broad based and sustained bilateral dialogue.
</P>
<P>
In response to Pakistan's offer for a moratorium on nuclear
testing as well as peace talks, India Friday proposed June 22 for
the resumption of the dialogue between the two neighbors at the
foreign secretary level in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan quickly rejected the proposal as "traditional
gimmickry" and accused India of sabotaging the dialogue between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The India spokesman listed the recent positive gestures made by
New Delhi including a moratorium on nuclear testing, its
willingness to explore ways and means for de jure formalization of
this undertaking, readiness to engage in negotiations on a fissile
material cut-off treaty and continuance of strict export controls
on nuclear-related materials and technologies.
</P>
<P>
"It is a matter of regret that the G-8 foreign ministers joint
communique has not taken into account these proposals but has
instead repeated unrealistic prescriptions, couched in the
language of pressure," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
India would continue to take decisions on the basis of its own
assessment and national security requirements, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0145 </DOCNO>
