<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers are as follows:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- In a bid to support reform of grain distribution system,
more than 3,000 auditing workers in Henan Province, a leading
grain producer in central China, have been dispatched to grassroot
grain enterprises to audit financial accounts there, draw a clear
line of responsibilities and make suggestions.
</P>
<P>
--The Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) announced in Beijing
that it will take the lead in the country in the implementation
of a national knowledge innovation program.
</P>
<P>
--Both Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, and Li Ruihuan, Chairman of
the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC), met in Beijing with Alain Juppe,
former French prime minister who is now mayor of Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
--China will launch European satellite for the first time.
A telecommunications satellite made by the National Aerospatial
Company of France arrived at the Xichang Satellite Launch Center
in southwest China's Sichuan Province yesterday.
</P>
<P>
--Information from the Ministry of Agriculture says that China
is expecting another bumper summer grain harvest this year
following the record summer grain harvest of 1997.
</P>
<P>
So far, wheat harvesting in the country's major wheat growing
provinces such as Jiangsu, Anhui and Henan provinces has been
finished thanks to the help of trans-regional machine harvesting
teams.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China will allow more enterprises to list shares on overseas
markets, while also considering ways to attract more foreign
investors to the country's B-share market, a top securities
official says.
</P>
<P>
-- China will revitalize the silk sector, which made two
billion yuan in economic losses last year for excess processing
capacity, by focusing on cutting back the expansion of
silk-spinning plants, a key production link that is creating
oversupply and pushing up the demand for silkworm cocoons, a top
silk official says.
</P>
<P>
-- China is carrying out a major realignment of its refining
and petrochemical industry, including the scaling down of smaller,
local refineries, a petrochemical official said. 
</P>
