<HEADLINE> No Travel Ban for Soeharto: Indonesian Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- There had been no request from
Indonesian authorities to stop former president Soeharto traveling
overseas, The Sunday Observer quoted a minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The Immigration Office only just waits for requests. Up to now
there has been no request to ban Soeharto," said Justice Minister
Muladi Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Muladi said he was sure Soeharto would stay in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The attorney-general, Finance Ministry or military headquarters
all have the power to request travel bans which are administered
by the Immigration Office.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto and his family have been the focus of public criticism
since he stepped down on May 21, accused of accumulating massive
wealth during his 32 years in office.
</P>
<P>
The attorney-general office recently launched an investigation
into the wealth of former government officials, including Soeharto
and his family.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Soeharto had hired Yohannes Yacob, an
Indonesian lawyer, to represent him during the attorney-general's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Yacob told Antara News Agency Saturday that he had met with
Attorney General Soedjono C. Atmonegoro in his capacity as
Soeharto's legal representative.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Yacob said, he submitted to the attorney
general a number of documents about the foundations managed by or
linked to Soeharto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
