<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Soccer Has A long Way to Go </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada's soccer will have a long
way to go before it could compete seriously with the best in the
world, says a Canadian soccer expert.
</P>
<P>
The country failed to qualify for the ongoing World Cup in
France, it was beaten, even by the Caribbean island of Jamaica,
where a mere 10,000 play the game.
</P>
<P>
Eric King, former executive director of the Canadian Soccer
Association, suggested it could be two more generations before
Canada can realistically compete with the best as today's kids
carry a love of soccer into adulthood and teach it to their
children.
</P>
<P>
Only then will there be the solid base of soccer-first
Canadians to demand more television coverage, to deserve better
facilities and to command enough attention to attract big money
from sponsors, King said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the lacklustre status quo of Canadian soccer to
"a high standard of living" in the country, where kids go to the
cinema or play games instead of playing their way out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Another major factor is that soccer is still perceived in
Canada as a game played by foreigners, King said in a newspaper
interview published here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
For now, Canadians for whom soccer is a religion are likely to
be Canadians born into a soccer culture, such as
Italian-Canadians, Brazilian-Canadians and Scottish-Canadians.
</P>
<P>
"These people still support the visiting team when it comes to
play Canada," King noted.
</P>
<P>
The soccer expert predicted that it "will take two generations
before the game is embedded in this country." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
