<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's China Trip: A Fresh Impetus to Sino-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- In less than two weeks' time, Bill
Clinton will be the first U.S. president to touch down in Beijing
since 1989, and the visit, high on the agenda of the host as well
as the guest, is to bring new driving force for their relations.
</P>
<P>
China and the U.S. Warm up for Another Summit
</P>
<P>
A new stage in the expansion of Sino-U.S. relations began with
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's travel half way around the world
on an official visit to the United States between October 16 and
November 3 last year. It marked the returning of the bilateral ties
back onto the track for steady, healthy and lasting growth.
</P>
<P>
Since Jiang's U.S. tour, high-level exchanges, dialogues and
cooperative efforts between the two countries have been striking a
positive tone and proven fruitful on new grounds, creating an
atmosphere favorable to Clinton's upcoming visit to
China. Noticeable developments are as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- High ranking Chinese and U.S. officials have been meeting at
a high frequency rare in the past. U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Secretary of Defense William Cohen, and other
Clinton administration officials have toured China since the
beginning of the year. And in April alone, four U.S. officials
above the vice-ministerial rank were in Beijing. In addition,
during Albright's stay in China, the two sides agreed to a
presidential communications link between Beijing and
Washington. It was via this hot line that Jiang and Clinton
recently discussed bilateral issues and developments in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
-- China and the United States have been working more closely
together in science and technology, economy and trade, and
education and culture. In March, the Sino-U.S. cooperation accord
on the peaceful use of nuclear energy finally came into effect 13
years after it was signed. And earlier in the year, President
Clinton gave green light to U.S. companies for cooperation with
their Chinese counterparts in commercial satellites launching,
paving the way for the Loral Space Systems of the United States
and the Great Wall Industry Corp. of China to sign a multiple
launch services contract, which was signed on March 16. In a
related development on March 26, China's Long March 2C space
rocket successfully carried two Iridium communications satellites
into a low earth orbit for Motorola Corporation of the United
States. Chinese and American scientists also worked jointly on a
project to experiment materials in the space.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing and Washington have increased dialogues on human
rights issues. In March, the Clinton administration said it would
no longer co-sponsor a resolution against China at the annual
United Nations meeting on human rights. And upon China's
announcement of its plan to sign the Covenant on Political and
Civil Rights, the U.S. side immediately let out positive
responses. Chinese and American religious delegations exchanged
visits in the first quarter of the year, which helped a lot in
deepening mutual understanding on religious and human rights
issues.
</P>
<P>
-- China and the United States have also been stepping up
exchanges and cooperation on security issues. During U.S. Defense
Secretary Cohen's stay in China, the two sides forged an agreement
on establishing a consultation mechanism to strengthen maritime
military safety. And right after India's nuclear testing in May,
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and U.S. Secretary of State
Albright were over the phone to evaluate the security situation in
South Asia.
</P>
<P>
-- On the issue of Taiwan, an inalienable part of China,
Clinton administration officials have repeatedly reiterated the
U.S. commitment to observe the "one China" policy in line with
principles set forth in the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques and
the joint statement. They have reaffirmed that the United States
will never support Taiwan's independence and its entry into the
United Nations or any other international organizations grouping
together sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
-- In addition, there has been a shift in U.S. public opinions
toward China since President Jiang's U.S. tour, with the
mainstream media taking an approach more objective than in the
past in covering China-related events. More and more Americans are
turning their backs on the China-bashing propaganda operations by
anti-China forces.
</P>
<P>
Clinton Brushes off Opposition to Move Up China Tour
</P>
<P>
In March, President Clinton announced moving up his China tour
from initially planned fall to the current schedule of summer. He
adamantly rejected some legislators' call for postponing or even
cancelling the trip, saying that the tour is too important to be
put off.
</P>
<P>
As the White House's travel schedule shows, Clinton's visit to
China is exclusive, with no stops in other countries. Such an
arrangement reflects the high priority given by the U.S. president
to Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's China Trip: A Fresh Impetus to Sino-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It's recognizable that there are some elements of partisan
politics behind Clinton's decision, but it's more likely that the
following factors prompt him to move ahead:
</P>
<P>
-- Firstly, the success of President Jiang's visit to the
United States has laid a solid foundation and created favorable
conditions for the bilateral relations to grow into the next
century. Clinton seems to feel the need to hitchhike on the trend
and push further ahead the strategic partnership between the two
countries. As stated in his recent letter to Jiang, Clinton is
looking forward to visiting China and building on the momentum
gained during the Chinese president's U.S. visit.
</P>
<P>
-- Secondly, China's role in stabilizing the Asian economy has
been growing, especially since a financial crisis broke out in
East Asia later last year. China has committed itself not to
devaluate the Chinese currency renminbi and provided billions of
U.S. dollars to help the hardest-hit countries in the region. The
United States, which has mounting business interests at stake in
East Asia, is in need to coordinate with China in search for ways
to lead the region out of the quagmire. As the financial crisis
is still going on, Clinton feels it increasingly urgent to have
China's support in preventing the crisis from preying on the
80-month-old U.S. economic growth. Further more, the United States
is eager to further explore the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
-- Thirdly, destabilizing elements have been on the rise on the
Korean peninsula and in Southeast and South Asia in recent years,
posing new threats to U.S. strategic interests in the
Asian-Pacific region. The recent nuclear testings by India and
Pakistan have dealt a severe blow to nuclear non-proliferation,
which tops the U.S. global security agenda in the post-Cold War
era. To maintain regional and global security interests of the
United States, the Clinton administration needs to engage and work
with China, a regional heavy-weight in safeguarding stability and
security on the western side of the Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
-- Lastly, the emerging trend, at the turn of century, of
building bilateral partnerships among major powers also acts as a
catalyst to Clinton's decision to move ahead his China tour. Since
President Jiang visited the United States last fall, China has
further improved its relations with Russia, the European Union and
Japan, which compels the White House to catch up by rescheduling
Clinton's China trip.
</P>
<P>
Common Interests Outweigh Differences
</P>
<P>
Due to differences in social systems, cultural background and
historical traditions, China and the United States still have
different views on some major issues. It is noteworthy that some
anti-China forces in the United States are doing their utmost to
make noises against the growth of the Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Last November, right after President Jiang's visit, the
U.S. Senate passed eight anti-China bills. And recently, the House
of Representatives passed four amendments to curb President
Clinton's policy of constructively engaging China. More recently,
some congressional sub-committees alleged that Clinton's approval
of Sino-U.S. joint satellite launch programs allowed Chinese
access to sensitive U.S. missile technologies.
</P>
<P>
The two sides still differ on trade imbalance, market access
and China's bid for entry into the World Trade Organization. The
United States is continuing to mount pressures onto China on
issues concerning human rights, religious freedom and Tibet. In
addition, some people in the United States view China as a
potential rival in global security and advocate the combination of
"force and respect" when dealing with China. On the Taiwan issue,
some Americans have been trying hard to press China into a
commitment not to use force under any circumstances in the course
of reunification. They also hold that the U.S. policy of arms
sales to Taiwan remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Despite the anti-China noises, the Clinton administration's
policy of engagement and dialogue with China has become even more
popular among Americans, and the call for stronger ties between
the United States and China has been growing even louder,
especially since President Jiang's visit to the United
States. History proves that differences between nations should not
prevent them from cooperating closely since they can always find
out some common ground in pursuit of their own interests.
</P>
<P>
It is our belief that China and the United States can enhance
mutual understanding, broaden consensus and work more closely
together as long as they follow the principles set forth in the
three joint communiques and the joint statement, and take a
positive, pragmatic and rational approach in seeking their common
interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shortage of Parking Places Headache for Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Beijing needs 1.5 million parking
places for the over 1.2 million motor vehicles now running on its
streets.
</P>
<P>
This calculation, carried in Thursday's ``China Youth Daily'',
is based on the theory every car needs 1.3 parking spots, with the
one referring to a fixed place and the other 0.3 to a shared
public place.
</P>
<P>
However, there are only over 50,000 parking places in the
Chinese capital, far short of the practical need. This means 30
cars have to vie for one parking place.
</P>
<P>
As early as in June 1989, the municipal government began to
stipulate that all restaurants of over 1,000 sq m, cinemas of over
2,000 sq m, and hotels, office buildings, shops, hospitals,
exhibition centers, theaters and gymnasiums of over 5,000 sq m
must have parking places or garages built. Those which fail to
meet the requirement will be fined.
</P>
<P>
In a recent move for improvement, the public transport
authorities designated 26 major downtown streets as "demonstration
parking streets". All of the streets have special areas for
parking. By the end of this year the number of such streets will
be increased to 80.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the authorities have stiffened penalties for
violators of parking rules.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
