<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aging Population Up in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The aging population of
Argentina's total population went up 0.7 percentage points from
8.2 percent in 1980 to the current 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figure is expected to reach 10.3 percent by the year of
2010, the latest report of the National Institute of Statistics
and Census (INDEC) said.
</P>
<P>
By then, Argentina will boast the second highest senior
population rate among Latin American countries, following Uruguay
with 12.4 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that by the year of 2050, 17.8 percent of
Argentina's population will be old people, with an average of 20
percent of women and 15.5 percent of men.
</P>
<P>
The report considers as the main causes of the growing aging
population the longer life expectancy and the lower fertility and
mortality rates.
</P>
<P>
The INDEC statistics showed that life expectancy in Argentina
grew from 68.9 to 71.9 years during the past 10 years, while the
rate of fertility dropped from 3.3 to 2.9 children per woman, the
lowest in the history of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
