<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, June 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq and the U.N. Special Commission on Disarmament
in Iraq, or UNSCOM, held the second round of talks later Saturday
in a bid to solve the dispute over the U.N. weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz headed the Iraqi team,
while UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler was leading the UNSCOM
delegation. (Iraq-UNSCOM-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A senior Jordanian official attacked Saturday the
practice of applying sanctions on some Arab countries, saying the
only victims are innocent people.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister for Services and Minister of Information
Abdullah Ensour launched the attack following the Cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
He referred to countries such as Iraq, Libya and Sudan, which
are all under international sanctions for one reason or another
and are facing subsequent serious economic difficulties.
(Jordan-Arab-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Iran Saturday signed a protocol for
bilateral cooperation in the fields of industry and investment,
the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, signed by the head of the Egyptian Industries
Federation, Abdel Monem Saudi, and the Iranian chief of Mining,
Trade and Industry Federation, Ali Khamoush, aims to increase and
develop trade exchange as well as bilateral cooperation in
industrial and investment spheres. (Egypt-Iran-Trade Team)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON - Japan's confirmation of its recession has caused fears
here that it could drag the West into economic decline.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the recession announcement Friday, the Dow Jones
industrial average on Wall Street plunged another 100 points
during afternoon trading. Here in London, the FTSE 100 index fell
82.7 points to close at 5,769.8.
</P>
<P>
Official figures published show that Japan's gross domestic
product shrank by 1.3 percent in the three months to the end of
March, equivalent to a decline at an annual rate of 5.3 percent.
(West-Japan-Recession)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- NATO announced Saturday that it is conducting mock
air raids next Monday in Albania and Macedonia to demonstrate its
capability to project power into the region rapidly.
</P>
<P>
The Western military alliance first announced air exercises in
the two Balkan countries at its defense ministers council meeting
Thursday, but did not say when. (NATO-Air Exercises) 
</P>
