<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Gets Ready for Tropical Storm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Mexico maintained a state of
alert Saturday as tropical storm "Agatha" approached the country
at 95 kilometers an hour.
</P>
<P>
The National Water Commission said the storm, capable of
producing heavy rains in the south and center of the country, was
only 550 kilometers away from the Mexican Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
The National Meteorological Service alerted maritime and port
authorities and small craft navigation about the wind velocity and
up to 10 feet (three meter) high waves.
</P>
<P>
The influence of humidity in the air blowing from the Pacific,
Gulf of Mexico, and Caribbean Sea will produce cloudy skies and
rains on most of the south and center of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, weather conditions of isolated clouds and rains will
be reinforced by a jet current that traverses all Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
