<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Faithful to Commitments to NATO: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Romania will be faithful to its
commitments and will take action in line with those of NATO as
regards former Yugoslavia, Romanian Defense Minister Victor Babiuc
said Saturday at Otopeni Airport upon his return from Copenhagen
and Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Babiuc made the statement commenting on what Foreign Minister
Andrei Plesu had said earlier in an interview with the daily
Adevarul (The Truth), namely "Romania could not fail to honor its
commitments to the Contact Group, if NATO declared war to
Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
Plesu also said in the interview that the Romanians hope from
the bottom of their heart that military solutions would be shunned
and political dialogue would have the last word. "We are also
against all sorts of separatist movements. Any separatism in our
region is extremely dangerous," he added.
</P>
<P>
Back in Romania after a journey with two stays, Victor Babiuc
said that in Copenhagen he had concluded an agreement on bilateral
military cooperation, and in Brussels he attended the
Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council meeting, with the agenda
including key issues such as the strengthening of the Partnership
for Peace and the situation in Bosnia and especially in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980614.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov: Russia Opposes NATO Inclusion of Baltic State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov Saturday reiterated Moscow's opposition to Baltic states'
membership in NATO.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister, who was on a brief working visit to
Lithuania, told reporters in Vilnius that the Baltic countries'
accession to NATO "is not acceptable to us because it creates
certain threats and inconveniences for Russia, affects our
geopolitical and security interests."
</P>
<P>
However, he said Moscow welcomes and supports Lithuania's
integration with European economic structures.
</P>
<P>
"Lithuania's accession to European economic structures is a
decision which does not do harm to anyone," he said. "This is why
Russia supports such an aspiration of official Vilnius."
</P>
<P>
Primakov said Russia has unconditionally pulled out all of its
troops from the Baltic states, thus liquidating its military
presence there.
</P>
<P>
"We have a right to expect that the security of the Baltic
states can be ensured without a deployment of foreign troops which
would take the military infrastructure we have left voluntarily,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Russia has long been staunchly opposed to the Baltic states'
membership in the alliance, and has offered them security
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
However, Lithuanian Parliament Speaker Vytautas Landsbergis
told a delegation of Russian lawmakers early this month that
Vilnius could not accept the security guarantees because it was
not sure that Russia would follow a consistent, democratic path.
</P>
<P>
He said admission into the transatlantic military bloc remains
a foreign policy priority and is supported by all political
parties in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
