<HEADLINE> Iraqi Parliament Speaker Slams UNSCOM's Stalling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) Speaker Saddoun Hammadi Saturday slammed the stalling
tactics adopted by U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarmament
in Iraq when carrying out its mission in the country.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi said on Saturday evening at a session of the assembly
that Iraq had implemented all the requirements under
U.N. resolution 687 seven years ago, and that the Security
Council should be committed to its reciprocal and moral
obligations toward Iraq by lifting trade embargo as the first
step toward total lifting of the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States and Britain are to blame for all the
time that had been wasted previously and for all the damage
inflicted upon the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The speaker said that by adopting stalling tactics through
creating excuses and sparking crises, the UNSCOM is a partner in
the crimes committed by the U.S. and Britain toward Iraq people.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the UNSCOM has been doing its "dirty mission"
which is financed by Iraqi resources for seven years. During the
past seven years, the UNSCOM has sent altogether 253 inspection
teams to Iraq and conducted 2,553 visits throughout Iraq, Hammadi
said, adding that another 150 monitoring teams have paid 6,500
survey visits in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that these teams have found nothing to prove
the UNSCOM's false allegations, rather they have ascertained Iraq's
declaration that it is free of banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the process of coming and going and the game of
pretexts that have been played by the UNSCOM will not be endless, and
will be resisted by the Iraqi people and all Arabs.
</P>
<P>
While the speaker lashed out at the UNSCOM, UNSCOM Chairman
Richard Butler is in Baghdad to spell out new requirements for
Iraq to fulfill.
</P>
<P>
Butler and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz held the
first round of talks on Saturday morning on what Iraq must do
before sanctions imposed on it after its invasion of Kuwait in
1990 can be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Butler said here on Thursday that Iraq hasn't provided
adequated information on its biological weapons, and access to
information will be the main task for Iraq to fulfill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
