<HEADLINE> Jordan Condemns Sanctions on Arab Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official
attacked Saturday the practice of applying sanctions on some
Arab countries, saying the only victims are innocent people.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister for Services and Minister of Information
Abdullah Ensour launched the attack following the Cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
He referred to countries such as Iraq, Libya and Sudan, which
are all under international sanctions for one reason or another
and are facing subsequent serious economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The minister voiced the kingdom's strong opposition to what he
called "collective embargoes and sanctions," because such harsh
measures only harm the majority of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
It is fully regrettable to see the sanctions expanded to
engulf innocent people for political reasons that the people have
no hand in, Ensour told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government is very concerned about the sanctions
imposed on the three above-mentioned Arab countries and is looking
for ways to help lift them, he added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has signed an annual trade protocol with Iraq, under
which the kingdom is to export 255 million U.S. dollars worth of
food and medicines to Iraq in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian exports are believed to help Iraq alleviate the
economic crisis caused by the United Nations sanctions imposed in
1990 following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Jordan also maintains regular trade with Libya, whose volume
stood at 23 million U.S. dollars in 1996. The U.N. imposed
sanctions on Libya in 1992 after Libya refused to hand over two
suspects allegely involved in the Lockerbie air disaster, in which
270 passengers aboard a Pan Am plane were killed in an explosion
in Scotland in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordan has kept regular official contacts with Sudan
and provided medical and food supplies to Khartoum, which is under
U.N. sanctions since 1996 after it refused to hand over three
suspects allegedly involved in the 1995 assassination attempt
against Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
