<HEADLINE> Jordan Raps Settlement Expansion in E. Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official on
Saturday condemned the latest Israeli decision to build more
housing for Jewish settlers in the disputed East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Ensour, Deputy Prime Minister for Services and
Minister of Information, told reporters after the regular Cabinet
meeting that the Israeli government made its decision in disregard
of the international legitimacy and should be condemned by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Jordan opposes the Israeli government's decision because it is
carried out at the expanse of the "indigenous people," Ensour
said, referring to the dominant Palestinian population in East
Jerusalem which was seized by Israel from Jordan in the 1967 War.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed his regret over what he called Israeli
"arrogance" toward the United Nations resolutions and other peace
agreements it signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He warned Israel that it is dangerous to continue its policy
of expanding Jewish settlements in the occupied lands.
</P>
<P>
Ensour reiterated the Jordanian position that Jerusalem belongs
to the Arab people and the Palestinians have the right to
establish an independent state with the holy city as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Interior Ministry approved on June 9 to build 100
housing units for religious Jewish students near the Mount of
Olives in the Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
This was the latest in a series of recent settlement activities
in Jerusalem that have led to violent clashes and escalation of
the Israeli-Palestinian tensions at a time when the peace process
is deeply deadlocked. Palestinian officials have warned about dire
consequences caused by the continued Israeli provocation through
settlement expansion in the holy city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
