<HEADLINE> Iraq, UNSCOM Hold Second Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 13 (XINHUA)-- Iraq and the U.N. Special
Commission on disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM, held the second
round of talks later Saturday in a bid to solve the last dispute
over the U.N. weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz headed the Iraqi team,
while UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler was leading the UNSCOM
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Director of Iraqi Military Industry, Abdul-Tawab Mullah
Huwaish, Oil Minister Amir Mohammad Rasheed, Presidencial Office
Advisor Amir Al-Saadi also attended the the second meeting.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Saturday, the two sides held their first round of talks
at Iraqi Foreign Ministry's building.
</P>
<P>
No details of the first meeting were released, and neither
Butler nor Aziz talked to reporters. But some reports suggested
that progress has been made in the two rounds of talks.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi weapons officials said U.N. arms inspectors have already
uncovered enough weapons parts that could prove the Iraqi claims
that it had destroyed and buried its biological and chemical
missile warheads. The UNSCOM is currently examining these parts
before drawing a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived here on Thursday, leading a 20-member UNSCOM
delegation, including UNSCOM Deputy Chairman, American Charles
Duelfer and four UNSCOM commissioners from Venezuela, Russia,
Belgium and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The chief weapons inspector brought with him a road map which
lists what information Iraq should provide to prove that it has
destroyed all biological and chemical weapons and give a full
account of its production of VX nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
Butler complained Thursday that Iraq had not provided adequate
information on its biological program, adding that this will be
Iraq's main task to fulfill before sanctions imposed on it can be
lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
