<HEADLINE> Uganda's First Lady Urges Fight Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's first lady Janet
Museveni Saturday called upon district councils to set funds for
the fight against AIDS/HIV scourge in the eastern African
country.
</P>
<P>
She made the appeal when launching the International
Candlelight and AIDS Awareness Campaign in Kampala.
</P>
<P>
AIDS/HIV is a killer disease, so a full-scale struggle against
it is absolutely necessary, she noted.
</P>
<P>
She encouraged the Ugandans to participate in community-based
programs aimed at comforting the AIDS/HIV patients.
</P>
<P>
The first lady stressed the need for community involvement and
commitment, saying the battle against AIDS can only be won if all
members of the society take part in sensitizing each other about
the dangers of the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
Some 10 percent of Ugandans are HIV positive or suffer from
AIDS. About 500,000 people in the country, whose population
stands at 20 million, have died of AIDS since the first case was
reported in Uganda in 1982. 
</P>
