<HEADLINE> Iran Supports Further Oil Production Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran supports further cuts in
oil output in order to bolster the declining oil price on world
market, Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zanganeh said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready for further cuts if a deal is struck with the
others," Zanganeh said at the end of his short visit to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iran last week announced plans to cut its oil production by
100,000 barrels per day to boost the oil price following a visit
by Saudi Oil Minister Ali Bin Ibrahim al-Naimi to Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh described his talks with his Kuwaiti counterpart
Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah as "good," saying they focused on
discussing new cooperation plans in oil production.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for stronger cooperation among all oil
producing countries to shore up the oil price.
</P>
<P>
On his part, the Kuwaiti oil minister said oil producing
and exporting nations are facing critical situation due to the
sharp decline in oil price.
</P>
<P>
"There is a real crisis that requires us to make sacrifices
and curb production," Al-Sabah said, adding that producers within
and outside the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
have to cooperate to improve the market conditions.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah announced last Tuesday that Kuwait was prepared to
cut its oil production in an effort to boost the oil price,
which has dropped to low levels between 12 and 14 U.S. dollars per
barrel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
