<HEADLINE> Egypt, Iran Sign Protocol on Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Iran Saturday signed a
protocol for bilateral cooperation in the fields of industry and
investment, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, signed by Head of the Egyptian Industries
Federation Abdel Monem Saudi and Iranian Chief of Mining, Trade
and Industry Federation Ali Khamoush, aims to increase and
develop trade exchange as well as bilateral cooperation in
industrial and investment spheres.
</P>
<P>
The protocol provides for promoting joint investment,
exchanging data and holding joint exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian trade team, which arrived here on Thursday for a
five-day visit to Egypt, will continue talks with Egyptian
officials and businessmen on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The visit, the first of its kind in 20 years, comes as the two
countries seek to repair long-strained political ties and frozen
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
The visit followed one made by a delegation from the Egyptian
federation in March this year when the two sides discussed
prospects for holding an exhibition of Egyptian products in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to prepare for the executive steps
for holding the exhibition in a bid to elevate bilateral economic
and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
The sluggish Egyptian-Iranian economic cooperation was the
result of strained diplomatic and political relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government severed its diplomatic and political
relations with Egypt after the late Egyptian President Anwar
Sadat's visit to Israel and his peace initiative in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been trying to improve relations with its one-time foe
Egypt, which have strained since the 1979 Islamic Revolution and
worsened over accusations that Tehran was backing Muslim militants
fighting to overthrow Egypt's secular government.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' annual trade exchange in 1997 amounted to 75
million dollars, with Egypt's annual imports standing at 35 million
dollars and exports at 45 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iran is currently investing 220 million Egyptian pounds (64.7
million dollars) in seven projects of weaving, carpets, ready-made
garments and banks in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
